1

00:00:00,000  -->  00:00:03,080
Even though Python is a computer programming language,

2

00:00:03,080  -->  00:00:06,180
did you know that it can also make decisions?

3

00:00:06,180  -->  00:00:11,240
It's not so different from how you or I make decisions in our day to day lives.

4

00:00:11,240  -->  00:00:14,220
If it's rainy outside, wear a raincoat.

5

00:00:14,220  -->  00:00:17,305
So long as it's Monday to Friday, work.

6

00:00:17,305  -->  00:00:21,950
Or when it's Saturday or Sunday, rest and recharge.

7

00:00:21,950  -->  00:00:25,430
We make tons of decisions every single day,

8

00:00:25,430  -->  00:00:28,130
35,000 per day, in fact,

9

00:00:28,130  -->  00:00:29,850
according to Harvard Business Review.

10

00:00:29,850  -->  00:00:34,650
The way we make decisions is similar to Python in using conditions.

11

00:00:34,650  -->  00:00:37,750
Python calls these conditional statements,

12

00:00:37,750  -->  00:00:41,630
which you can think of as fact based observations of the world.

13

00:00:41,630  -->  00:00:45,910
The if statement is the most basic form of a conditional statement.

14

00:00:45,910  -->  00:00:51,710
Let's start with an example where we want to print the response to the input of age.

15

00:00:51,710  -->  00:00:55,020
In this function, we want to check if the provided age

16

00:00:55,020  -->  00:00:58,820
is greater than or equal to a certain integer.

17

00:00:58,820  -->  00:01:02,200
In this example, if the age is 18 or older,

18

00:01:02,200  -->  00:01:05,980
our Python program will print that you are eligible to vote.

19

00:01:05,980  -->  00:01:09,460
Otherwise, it prints that you are not eligible to vote.

20

00:01:09,460  -->  00:01:11,240
This way, we don't need to write

21

00:01:11,240  -->  00:01:15,320
two separate functions and then run each of them at the same time.

22

00:01:15,320  -->  00:01:17,480
We write this if statement,

23

00:01:17,480  -->  00:01:19,840
and then use a conditional statement while

24

00:01:19,840  -->  00:01:23,325
leveraging Python's built in logic and reasoning.

25

00:01:23,325  -->  00:01:25,830
When we think about conditional statements,

26

00:01:25,830  -->  00:01:28,170
let's see this in another example.

27

00:01:28,170  -->  00:01:30,970
This time, with a scoring system for exams.

28

00:01:30,970  -->  00:01:34,450
It would be so draining of our time if we needed to run

29

00:01:34,450  -->  00:01:40,685
four different functions to check if a score is 0-69 as an F,

30

00:01:40,685  -->  00:01:43,440
70-79 as a C,

31

00:01:43,440  -->  00:01:45,645
80-89 as a B,

32

00:01:45,645  -->  00:01:48,090
and 90-100 as an A.

33

00:01:48,090  -->  00:01:50,690
Doing this per student would be exhausting.

34

00:01:50,690  -->  00:01:54,510
Fortunately, for us, we can add more conditions using

35

00:01:54,510  -->  00:01:58,370
elif and else to check other conditional cases.

36

00:01:58,370  -->  00:02:03,450
It's much easier to see this as a visual. So check this out.

37

00:02:03,450  -->  00:02:06,110
We'll first define a variable called score,

38

00:02:06,110  -->  00:02:10,090
and this will be the score of a given student,

39

00:02:10,090  -->  00:02:12,650
which will set as 85.

40

00:02:12,650  -->  00:02:18,565
If this score is greater than or equal to 90,

41

00:02:18,565  -->  00:02:23,350
we'll say print. Grade is A.

42

00:02:23,390  -->  00:02:32,070
Then elif, score is greater than or equal to 80.

43

00:02:32,070  -->  00:02:37,795
We'll say print, grade B.

44

00:02:37,795  -->  00:02:39,960
We'll do another elif statement,

45

00:02:39,960  -->  00:02:45,170
and we'll say elif score greater than or equal to 70,

46

00:02:45,170  -->  00:02:47,660
and then say print,

47

00:02:47,660  -->  00:02:54,410
Grade C. Then else,

48

00:02:54,410  -->  00:02:58,875
so all other cases that aren't these.

49

00:02:58,875  -->  00:03:09,420
Say print, Grade F. The first check is if the score is greater than or equal to 90.

50

00:03:09,420  -->  00:03:15,560
Then the next band is if it's greater than or equal to 80 after 90 and so on,

51

00:03:15,560  -->  00:03:19,400
to classify the grade as being between these scoring bands.

52

00:03:19,400  -->  00:03:22,780
We don't need to write the same function for different times.

53

00:03:22,780  -->  00:03:25,275
All we have to do is this,

54

00:03:25,275  -->  00:03:28,305
if, elif, else statement.

55

00:03:28,305  -->  00:03:31,050
Let's run this to see what happens.

56

00:03:31,050  -->  00:03:35,640
So when the score is 85, the grade is B.

57

00:03:35,640  -->  00:03:40,650
Then let's say if we change this to be 75.

58

00:03:40,650  -->  00:03:49,450
We see that the grade is C. If we made this 99, grade A.

59

00:03:49,460  -->  00:03:56,910
Of course, if we got score of 50, we get this.

60

00:03:56,910  -->  00:04:00,285
If we even do 90,

61

00:04:00,285  -->  00:04:06,015
we get grade A. Pretty neat.

62

00:04:06,015  -->  00:04:09,090
In the next section, we'll learn how to expand

63

00:04:09,090  -->  00:04:12,375
upon this conditional logic with some other cases.

64

00:04:12,375  -->  00:04:15,740
Now that we've introduced the basic concepts of conditional statements,

65

00:04:15,740  -->  00:04:19,280
let's break them down further into three main types of conditional statements.

66

00:04:19,280  -->  00:04:23,140
If else, if elif and if elif else.

67

00:04:23,140  -->  00:04:26,480
Understanding these will be essential as we progress into

68

00:04:26,480  -->  00:04:30,900
more complex conditional logic that we can use in our Python code.

69

00:04:30,900  -->  00:04:35,040
The if-else statement is the most straightforward conditional structure.

70

00:04:35,040  -->  00:04:37,560
It checks a single condition, and if it's true,

71

00:04:37,560  -->  00:04:41,240
it executes one block of code, the true case.

72

00:04:41,240  -->  00:04:43,260
If the condition is false,

73

00:04:43,260  -->  00:04:46,930
it jumps to the else block and executes that instead.

74

00:04:46,930  -->  00:04:50,550
In this example, if the score is 70 or higher,

75

00:04:50,550  -->  00:04:53,690
the message, you passed the exam is printed.

76

00:04:53,690  -->  00:04:55,530
Otherwise, the exam prints,

77

00:04:55,530  -->  00:04:57,210
sorry, you didn't pass.

78

00:04:57,210  -->  00:05:01,770
This allows us to handle two mutually exclusive outcomes efficiently,

79

00:05:01,770  -->  00:05:07,690
where one is either true or if it's not true, it's automatically false.

80

00:05:07,690  -->  00:05:09,510
In this grading example,

81

00:05:09,510  -->  00:05:11,170
the conditions are similar,

82

00:05:11,170  -->  00:05:14,230
but now we've added a default response grade F,

83

00:05:14,230  -->  00:05:17,570
where if the score doesn't meet any of the previous criteria,

84

00:05:17,570  -->  00:05:19,660
then a grade F is presented.

85

00:05:19,660  -->  00:05:22,410
This ensures that all possible cases are

86

00:05:22,410  -->  00:05:26,930
handled before sending the final default response back.

87

00:05:26,930  -->  00:05:30,180
Next up, we have the if-elif structure.

88

00:05:30,180  -->  00:05:34,280
This is very useful when you need to check multiple conditions.

89

00:05:34,280  -->  00:05:37,460
Python evaluates each condition in sequence and

90

00:05:37,460  -->  00:05:41,120
executes the block of the first condition that is true.

91

00:05:41,120  -->  00:05:43,220
Here, we're grading an exam.

92

00:05:43,220  -->  00:05:46,860
If the score is 90 or higher, the student gets an A.

93

00:05:46,860  -->  00:05:50,660
If it's 80-89, the student gets a B.

94

00:05:50,660  -->  00:05:54,980
Notice how the code stops checking once a true condition is found.

95

00:05:54,980  -->  00:05:58,780
This is the power of Python's conditional logic in using

96

00:05:58,780  -->  00:06:02,880
our relational operators to create these assessment bands.

97

00:06:02,880  -->  00:06:06,285
Finally, we have the if-elif-else structure.

98

00:06:06,285  -->  00:06:11,380
This is a more comprehensive conditional statement where we check multiple conditions,

99

00:06:11,380  -->  00:06:13,120
and if none of them are true,

100

00:06:13,120  -->  00:06:17,840
a default action defined by the else block is executed.

101

00:06:17,840  -->  00:06:19,640
In this grading example,

102

00:06:19,640  -->  00:06:21,100
the conditions are similar,

103

00:06:21,100  -->  00:06:23,660
but now we've added a default response, grade F,

104

00:06:23,660  -->  00:06:27,200
where if the score didn't meet any of the previous criteria,

105

00:06:27,200  -->  00:06:29,320
then a grade F is presented.

106

00:06:29,320  -->  00:06:32,000
This ensures that all possible cases are handled

107

00:06:32,000  -->  00:06:35,660
before setting the final default response back.
